records.addlTxt:
Defendant Dylan J W Spriggs in court with attorney Jeffrey Murrell.  
Jesica Ballenger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Matter before the Court for Sentencing.  Hearing proceeded.  Statements made by Jasmine S., State, and Defense counsel.
  
AS TO COUNT 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 1/2 YEARS, with credit for 12 DAYS time served.

THE INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 1/2 YEARS.
THE MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program.  

AS TO COUNT 2:  The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 9 MONTHS of imprisonment, concurrent to Count 1.

The Court STAYED these sentences and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 3 YEARS:

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION (if revoked):
1) As to Count 1 ONLY: Serve 9 months in the House of Correction with release for employment and treatment -STAYED to 3-16-16, 12p.m.; 
2) Obtain an AODA assessment and  complete any recommended follow-up care/treatment;
3) Obtain Sex offender evaluation and complete any recommended follow-up care/treatment;
4) No Contact with victim A.U.H. (DOB 6/21/05);
5) Provide a DNA sample - pay surcharge;
6) Pay all mandatory costs, fees, surcharges and assessments by the end of probation period- any balance to covert to civil judgment.;
7) Follow any rules deemed appropriate by Department of Corrections;

The Court sets restitution set at ZERO.  If revoked all court costs, fines, surcharges to be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  

**Defendant ordered to comply with sex offender reporting for TEN (10) YEARS** 
**Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting**  

The Court rules that if EACH condition of probation is completed WITH NO VIOLATIONS the defendant may petition the court for possible expungement.  
The Court advised the defendant of his right to appeal this sentence.
